SIMPLE: enchantment
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Enchantment
<hw>En*chant"ment</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>enchantement</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of enchanting;
the production of certain wonderful effects by the aid of demons, or the
agency of supposed spirits; the use of magic arts, spells, or charms;
incantation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After the last <qex>enchantment</qex> you did here.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The effect produced by the act; the state of being
enchanted; <as>as, to break an <ex>enchantment</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which captivates the heart and senses; an
influence or power which fascinates or highly delights.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such an <qex>enchantment</qex> as there is in words.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Incantation; necromancy; magic; sorcery;
witchcraft; spell; charm; fascination; witchery.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Enchantress</ent>⟦br⟧
